Meeting - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday's tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Québec has become one of the world's safest and most effective blood suppliers.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously removed from the blood-infected scandal in the years from 1980 to 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus in the 1980s.
In the face of such a drama and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public investigation in February 1994 , led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the reproposal of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was delaying a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of developing a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, 38% of the people said that they still had confidence in the system of donations in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalled.
The situation was killing.
Thanks to the continued efforts to improve the safety of blood collection and field research over the years, we have regained public confidence," he said, before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "confidence is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of foundation.
"And we didn't know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It is therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports that when you have doubts and you may have a serious illness, in this case the patient of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, who manifests a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, will take measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than one month in the United Kingdom was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that there is no doubt that this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has shown us so that it has made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999 a much more efficient technique for identifying HIV appeared on the market: nuclear acid (TAN) tests that directly recognize the presence of the virus in the donor blood and not that of antibodies against it, on which the tests used so far were based.
TAN allowed to reduce the window period, i.e. since the person contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them is thus significantly reduced.
These improvements have resulted in a significant reduction in the risk of anti-AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one out of 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV has been reported with a transfusion.
I believe that today you can feel calm about receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to restore health, says Hema-Quebec's head.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the Réunion Island that, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by an insect.
It must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continues before stressing that, in addition to having safe resources, Hema-Quebec must also provide sufficient resources.
"The needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
Being the most aggressive cancer cure, patients often need a contribution of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the number of donors, which on average account for only 3% of Quebec's population is acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who are 18 years old and who meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of those offering themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is spread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we can maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
The cases of poverty are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they age and cannot make any more donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold it and encourage it to become regular donors.
Today's life is so frenetic that it is difficult to find an hour to donate blood," says poor Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, eyelids and skin heart valves that are used almost exclusively for severe use.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before they are deposited with Hema-Québec, which manages the only public bank of the umbelic cord blood in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which once was considered a biomedical discharge, there is plenty of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion into the bank of our thousandth blood sample of cordon and we expect to take more than a thousand each year.
It should begin with proposals for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of taking cord blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to you," because Hema-Québec does not have the means necessary to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
