The intelligent machine imitates the flight of calabron
What might be the best way to develop anti-cancer technologies if you do not imitate the sensors of the obstacles that are in nature?
For example, those bees.
In the amazing project presented to the CEATEC in Japan, the calabrons gave the initial strategic tip to the engineers Nissan on how to build the next generation of anti-cancer systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotized miniauto with the properties of bees, with the aim of creating a system capable of scanning all collisions.
Flying the bees form their own oval personal space that really resembles our protective shield - explained to Kazuhiro Two, director of PR technology and research and development.
The role of the ape view is important, capable of a 300-degree view in each direction.
The engineers focused on the idea of telemetric laser to copy the function of the monkey view.
The BR23C detects the obstacles up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately transforms it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the monkey, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the incident.
This policy of avoiding, unlike the current system, is carried out in an instinctive manner.
"If it weren't for that, the robot car wouldn't react quickly to avoid collisions" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot auto project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the harmful and more internal layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a monkey does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in an eyeball.
But unlike the bees, the deviation cannot go up or down or in diagonal, it can only be bidimensional and in the direction of wheel steering.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow.
The BR23C is fed from batteries to lithium polymers, lighter and with high energy density, which means that their duration is higher than that of lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantaneity of the intelligent reaction, not the processing of data, or even less the ability to store them, is important.
This robot must produce some inputs in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on the previous manoeuvre data, so it only uses a memory of a few decades of Kb.
There's no need for a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, they foresee to Nissan, can be installed on serial vehicles within 10 years.
Further application options can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system which, by avoiding obstacles on the road, leads to destination.
